# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: caprotti-valve-gear
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **2-8-0** represents the wheel arrangement of two leading wheels on one axle, usually in a leading truck, eight powered and coupled driving wheels on four axles, and no trailing wheels.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In the United States and elsewhere, this wheel arrangement is commonly known as a **Consolidation**, after the Lehigh and Mahanoy Railroad’s *Consolidation*, the name of the first 2-8-0.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The notation **2-8-0T** indicates a tank locomotive of this wheel arrangement, the "T" suffix indicating a locomotive on which the water is carried in side-tanks mounted on the engine rather than in an attached tender.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Consolidation represented a notable advance in locomotive power.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Of all the locomotive types that were created and experimented with in the 19th century, the 2-8-0 was a relative latecomer.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The first locomotive of this wheel arrangement was possibly built by the Pennsylvania Railroad (PRR).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Like the first 2-6-0s, this first 2-8-0 had a leading axle that was rigidly attached to the locomotive's frame, rather than on a separate truck or bogie.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] To create this 2-8-0, PRR master mechanic John P.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Laird modified an existing 0-8-0, the *Bedford*, in 1863.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-6-0 Mogul type, first created in the early 1860s, is often considered as the logical forerunner to the 2-8-0.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] However, a claim is made that the first true 2-8-0 engine evolved from the 0-8-0 and was ordered by the United States' Lehigh and Mahanoy Railroad, which named all its engines.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The name given to the new locomotive was *Consolidation*, the name that was later almost globally adopted for the type.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] According to this viewpoint, the first 2-8-0 order by Lehigh dates to 1866 and antedates the adoption of the type by other railways and coal and mountain freight haulers.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] From its introduction in 1866 and well into the early 20th century, the 2-8-0 design was considered to be the ultimate heavy-freight locomotive.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-8-0's forte was starting and moving "impressive loads at unimpressive speeds" and its versatility gave the type its longevity.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The practical limit of the design was reached in 1915, when it was realised that no further development was possible with a locomotive of this wheel arrangement.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] As in the United States, the 2-8-0 was also a popular type in Europe, again largely as a freight hauler.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The type was also used in Australia, New Zealand, and Southern Africa.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-8-0 locomotive was used extensively throughout Australia.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It served on the 5 ft 3 in (1,600 mm) broad gauge, 4 ft 8+1⁄2 in (1,435 mm) standard gauge and 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) narrow gauge and was employed mostly as a freight locomotive, although it was often also employed in passenger service in Victoria.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The first Australian locomotive class with this wheel arrangement were the Queensland Railways C13 and C15, built as goods locomotives in 1879 by Baldwin Locomotive Works.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Another lot of Consolidation engines consisted of 20 standard-gauge New South Wales Government Railways (NSWGR) J Class engines, which arrived from Baldwin Locomotive Works in 1891.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Js remained in service until 1915, when they were withdrawn.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Wartime shortages between 1916 and 1920 had six engines re-entering service after being shopped and fitted with superheaters.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The last engine of this class was finally withdrawn in 1934 and all were scrapped by 1937.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The next batch of NSW 2-8-0 locomotives to appear, between 1896 and 1916, was the T class engines.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The class was delivered from one local and several overseas builders, 151 locomotives from Beyer, Peacock & Company, 84 from North British Locomotive Company, 10 from Neilson & Company, 30 from Clyde Engineering in Australia, and five from Dübs & Company.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] During World War II, 14 of these locomotives were equipped with superheaters, which raised their tractive effort from 28,777 lbf (128.0 kN) to 33,557 lbf (149.3 kN).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] From 1899, the Victorian Railways (VR) also used a range of broad-gauge 2-8-0 locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The first 2-8-0 engines in private service on the Midland Railway of Western Australia arrived in 1912.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These were 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) gauge locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The five in the class operated until 1958.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1912, some of the NSWGR T class types were also purchased by the private East Greta Railway, later to become the South Maitland Railway, but these were converted to 2-8-2 tank locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The class proved to be successful throughout its long service life, until being retired from government revenue service in 1973.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] During 1916, Commonwealth Railways acquired eight K class for the Trans-Australian Railway.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1924, a private coal company, J & A Brown in NSW, obtained three ex-British military Railway Operating Division ROD 2-8-0 locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Brown later ordered another 10 of these locomotives, but only nine of that order arrived in Australia.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] To compensate for wartime losses, Belgian railways acquired 300 2-8-0 locomotives in 1946.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were built in North America, 160 by Montreal Locomotive Works in Canada, 60 by the Canadian Locomotive Company, and 80 by the American Locomotive Company in the United States.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These machines proved to be very reliable and were used for mixed traffic until the end of the steam era, when number 29.013 hauled the last scheduled steam passenger train from Ath to Denderleeuw on 20 December 1966.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] This locomotive survived in preservation and is used on special excursions.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] On 16 December 2006, number 29.013 re-enacted the last 1966 run on the same route.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Canadian Pacific Railway (CP) N-2-a, b, and c class locomotives were a class of altogether 182 *Consolidation* type locomotives, built by Montreal Locomotive Works between 1912 and 1914.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were numbered in the range from 3600 to 3799 and were used almost everywhere around the system.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The order for these engines came about when CP needed bigger locomotives for their mainline since their current engines were wearing out and were too small for the loads that were being hauled.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Most of the class were converted to oil-firing in later years.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 3716, is run and maintained in Summerland, BC as part of the Kettle Valley Steam Railway.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Finland had five tender locomotive classes with a 2-8-0 wheel arrangement, the classes Tk1, Tk2, Tk3, Tv1, and Tv2.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The class Tk1s were numbered from 271 to 290 and were nicknamed *Amerikan Satikka*.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The class Tk2s were numbered 407 to 426 and 457 to 470.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 418 at Junction City, Oregon, in the United States, and No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were built by Tampella, Lokomo, and Frichs.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were built by Tampella and were nicknamed *Jumbo*.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 933 at the Veturi museum at Toijala, No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The class Tv2s were numbered from 618 to 637.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Finland had only one tank locomotive class with a 2-8-0 wheel arrangement, the class M1 consisting of one solitary locomotive numbered 66.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-8-0 wheel arrangement enjoyed a brief period of popularity in Germany during the era of the *Länderbahnen* or State Railways, from about 1840 to 1920, prior to the establishment after the First World War of the *Deutsche Reichsbahn*, the German National Railways.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Under the *Deutsche Reichsbahn-Gesellschaft* (DRG) classification system, all 2-8-0 locomotives were assigned to class 56 (*Baureihe* or BR 56), with different types receiving subclassifications.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The earliest type was the Prussian G73 of 1893.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These locomotives were made to fulfill the requirements that submitted by SS, being able to haul 550 tons of freight with speeds of up to 50 km/h (31 mph) or 30 km/h (18.6 mph) on lines with a gradient of 4% or 1 in 25.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In order to be able to negotiate 150 meters curve radius, the leading wheels adopted Adam axle system which could enable to turn radially by 70 mm.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] As for the fourth driving wheels, adopted *Golsdorf* axle system (patented by Karl Golsdorf), this make the outer driving wheels able to move laterally by 100 mm.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] As by result, it's not only able to turn at 150 meters curve radius, but speeds up to 75 km/h (46.6 mph) was made possible from its initial of 50 km/h (31 mph).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1939, the *Eendaagsche Express* shortened the time journey for Bandung–Yogyakarta–Surabaya to only 11 hours.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These locomotives worked on Bandung–Purwakarta–Batavia line and also assigned to work the eastern express trains in East Java on Banyuwangi–Surabaya line in tandem with 4-6-4T SS Class 1100 (DKA C27).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] To make the SS 900s have the characteristics of express locomotive, each unit received the modification of two pair of smoke deflectors.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In the need of increasing freight transport in South Sumatra, the Java Staatsspoorwegen allocated 4 of them to serve coal transport from Bukit Asam to Kertapati.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Not quite a long, the South Sumatra division of SS or so called *Zuid-Sumatra Staatsspoorwegen* (ZSS) were also ordered 11 of these from two German engine manufacturers, 5 were imported from Hartmann in 1925 and the rest of 6 from Hanomag in 1926.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] During Indonesian National Revolution some of SS Class 900/DKA D50 were used among the others to haul trains belonging to Republican fighters and the Dutch military.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In some records, some of them were destroyed in action due to the conflict.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] While the SS911 or DKA D50 11 was captured by 2nd Company of *1e Bataljon, 15 Regiment Infanterie* of Dutch Marines during Operation Kraai in Yogyakarta.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After the acknowledgement of Indonesian sovereignty by Dutch in 1949, the SS Class 900 were transferred to *Djawatan Kereta Api*.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1976, most of D50s were found regularly in Jember, East Java which many of them had been dumped out and seemed to be derelict.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] While the rest of them are still used regularly in South Sumatra pulling some coal trains.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Out of 61 units, only DKA D50 11 (ex-SS911) survived and now preserved as static display in Transportation Museum of Taman Mini Indonesia Indah.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Production of such locomotives, classified Gr.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 740 in Italy, began in 1911 and stopped four years later when Italy entered the First World War.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Thereafter, Italian industry was devoted to producing military equipment, so FS bought locomotives from North American firms.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] From 1917 to 1922, American Locomotive Company and Montreal Locomotive Works built 400 2-8-0 locomotives for Italy but only 393 were delivered.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 735 and used them for freight and passenger services.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After the war, the supply of Italian-built Gr.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 740 and Gr 735, very similar in performance, remained in service until the end of the 1960s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Baldwin supplied the first three 2-8-0 9000 class locomotives for export to Japan in 1893, in use of Hokkaido Colliery and Railway Company, which were taken over Japanese Government Railway under Railway Nationalization Act of 1906.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Among several classes, most successful examples were 770 of JNR Class 9600, built from 1913 to 1926.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Some independent shortlines had equivalent locomotives to 9600 both factory-new and secondhand from JNR, the last example was Yubari Colliery and Railway No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Despite obsolescence and early replacement by 2-8-2 D51, 9600s were still widely utilized thanks to high performance and appropriate route availability.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 79602, kept longevity until March 1976, making the very final steam traction in service on JNR.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 79602 was nearly preserved, however, sadly, it was subsequently destroyed by arson attack at Oiwake roundhouse.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Several 2-8-0 locomotives were supplied to New Zealand by the Baldwin Locomotive Works of Philadelphia in the United States.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Six O Class locomotives were built for the New Zealand Railways in 1885.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company, which operated the Wellington-Manawatu line, had four similar locomotives built by Baldwin, two in 1888, one in 1894 and one in 1896.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The WMR locomotives of 1894 and 1896, No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 13, were Vauclain compound locomotives, the first in New Zealand and the first narrow-gauge compounds in the world.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1908, when the WMR was nationalized, these locomotives were classified into three NZR subclasses because of detail differences, the two 1888 locomotives as OB class, the 1894 locomotive as OA class, and the 1896 locomotive as OC class.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Korean State Railway have locally built 500-series (used by rubber recycling plant) and 810 series Japanese built narrow gauge (762mm) 2-8-0 locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 810 series was likely retired in 2006 and 500-series may still be operating.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] "Consolidated" 2-8-0 locomotives were relatively popular at Polish State Railways (PKP) after 1918.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] However, most of them were not original polish designs.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After World War I newly created polish state took and introduced small amounts of 2-8-0 locomotives from Russia (Tr103), Germany (Tr1) and Austria-Hungary (Tr11 and Tr12).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Due to their wheel arrangement, they have been classified as "r" engines.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] First large order for new locomotives for PKP was made in United States in 1919.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were built in Baldwin Locomotive Works and classified in Poland as Tr20.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After World War II Poland acquired even more 2-8-0 engines, usually made in Germany in the interwar period, such as a Tr5 (former DRG Class 56.2), Tr6 (former Prussian G 8.2) and Tr7.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] More 2-8-0s came to Poland from United Kingdom and USA.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In years 1946 - 1976, PKP had 30 Liberation Class locomotives, classified as Tr202.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Another very popular staem engine was USATC S160.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] First 75 units came to Poland in the years 1946 - 1947 as part of the UNRRA program.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were classified as Tr201 from 1 to 75.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In the late 1940s Poland received 500 more S160 locomotives, later depicted as Tr203.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Last Tr201 and Tr203 were withdrawn in the early 1980s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] From almost 600 units only 3 remained in Poland: Tr203-451 in Warsaw, Tr201-51 and Tr203-296 in Jaworzyna Śląska.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The first 2-8-0 locomotives built in independent Poland were PKP class Tr12.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After 1918 PKP received 142 locomotives; 60 of them were built in early 1920s by WSABP in Warsaw.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Rest of those locomotives were delivered by Lokomotivfabrik Floridsdorf.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] First locomotive designed in Poland was Tr21.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] New steam engines for PKP were created in cooperation with Austrian StEG.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Between 1922 and 1925 PKP received 148 units of Tr21.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] There were 3 different producers: Austrian StEG, polish Fablok and Belgian John Cockerill.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] First locomotive fully built in Poland was Tr21-37 put into service in February 1924.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After World War II PKP had 100 units in service.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Usage of those locomotions ended in 1974.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Another Polish 2-8-0 locomotive was TKr55.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] TKr55 was a prototype steam engine designed in Poznań in 1955 and built in Wrocław in 1957.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] New unit was created for shunting operations.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It was based on the Tr203 (USATC S160) chassis, had a boiler similar to American locomotives and the cabine from the Polish TKt48.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The only prototype locomotive built was used in Kutno until late 1970s when it was scrapped.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In Russia, the 2-8-0 wheel arrangement was represented by the prerevolutionary Sch (Shuka-pike) class.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These two-cylinder compound locomotives without superheaters were declared the standard Russian freight locomotive in 1912, but since they were relatively low-powered, they were only useful on easier lines without steep gradients such as the Saint Petersburg-Moscow route.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Five 2-8-0 locomotive classes saw service in South Africa, all of them initially acquired by the Cape Government Railways (CGR), which classified all but two as 8th Class.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] All of them were variations on the same design, used saturated steam, and had cylinders with overhead slide valves, actuated by inside Stephenson valve gear.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] While subjecting the *Consolidation*s to exhaustive testing on all types of traffic and under varying conditions, some trouble was experienced with the leading pony truck and it was dropped in favour of a four-wheeled bogie in later orders for more eighth class locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] All subsequent Cape eighth class locomotives were therefore built with a 4-8-0 *Mastodon* wheel arrangement.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1907 and 1910, the *Staatsbahn Keetmanshoop* (Keetmanshoop State Railway) in German South West Africa placed 21 tank locomotives in service.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After the first World War, when all railways in the territory came under the administration of the South African Railways in 1922, five locomotives of the batch of 1910 survived.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] They were not classified or renumbered, but were referred to as the eight-coupled tanks.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1911, nine tender locomotives were placed in service by the *Staatsbahn Lüderitzbucht-Keetmanshoop* (Lüderitzbucht-Keetmanshoop State Railway).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After the first World War, all nine locomotives came onto the roster of the SAR, where they were referred to as the eight-coupled tenders.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The unusual M3t Turbine Steam Locomotive was of this type.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 90 of the Swedish E (0-8-0) class were rebuilt between 1935 and 1951 and given a lead truck, designated the class E2.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Turkey was a neutral country during the Second World War and to retain Turkish goodwill, Great Britain supplied several locomotives to the Turkish Railways, where they were classified 8F.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Two of these 8F class locomotives were brought back from Turkey early in 2011 and one of them is on display at the National Railway Museum in Shildon, England.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-8-0 gradually became the standard heavy-freight steam locomotive type in the United Kingdom during the first half of the 20th century, replacing the 0-8-0 types that had appeared as mineral locomotives in the 1890s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] These had themselves been a replacement for these heavier tasks of the 0-6-0 locomotives used for freight since the mid 19th century.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 0-6-0 remained a common type for lighter use and on branch lines, but the 0-8-0 largely disappeared in favour of the better-riding 2-8-0.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The first 2-8-0 to be built in Britain was the Great Western Railway's 2800 Class, with 84 locomotives built between 1903 and 1919, followed by a further 83 of the very similar GWR 2884 Class between 1938 and 1942.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1904, George Whale of the London and North Western Railway (LNWR) began to rebuild some of his predecessor's Class B 0-8-0 compound locomotives to 2-8-0, classes E and F.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] With coal trains increasing in size and scale, the GWR needed to develop a more powerful locomotive to meet these requirements, on what were relatively short haul routes.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Churchward took the basic design of his GWR 2800 Class, and adapted it.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After proposing a 2-8-2T design, Churchward developed the UK's first 2-8-0 tank engine, the 4200 class.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Robinson of the Great Central Railway (GCR) introduced his very successful GCR Class 8K for heavy freight.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 129 of these were originally built by the GCR.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] During the First World War, the design was adopted by the Ministry of Munitions and it became the standard locomotive of the Railway Operating Division of the Royal Engineers as the ROD 2-8-0.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Altogether, 521 of these ROD locomotives were built during the war.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] After the war, large numbers of these were purchased by the LNWR and GWR, while some were also sold to a private Australian coal company, J&A Brown in New South Wales.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Altogether, 273 were purchased by the LNWR during the early 1920s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Other successful 2-8-0 designs were built in the UK.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The GNR Class O1 and O2 were introduced by Nigel Gresley of the Great Northern Railway in 1913 and 1918, respectively, and the Class 7F by Henry Fowler of the Somerset and Dorset Joint Railway in 1914.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Whilst most British 2-8-0 designs were intended for heavy freight, the GWR 4700 Class were designed for heavy mixed-traffic work, but were initially employed mainly on fast overnight freight trains; later they were used on express excursions in the summer.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The most successful British 2-8-0 class was the Class 8F, designed in 1935 by William Stanier for the London, Midland and Scottish Railway.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] During the Second World War, the War Department originally chose the class 8F as its standard freight locomotive, and large numbers of them saw service overseas, notably in the Middle East.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Class 8F was superseded after 1943 by the cheaper WD Austerity 2-8-0 for war service.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] A total of 935 of these were built and again, many saw service overseas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In the United States, only a few railroads purchased *Consolidation* types when Baldwin Locomotive Works first introduced its version.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Even the Baltimore and Ohio railroad, which eventually had nearly 180 2-8-0 locomotives in regular service by 1885, did not purchase any of this type until 1873.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Buffalo, Rochester and Pittsburgh Railway, which eventually became part of B&O, purchased 15 of this type from Brooks Locomotive Works in 1883.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The 2-8-0 design was given a major boost in 1875, when the Pennsylvania Railroad made it their standard freight locomotive, and 1875 was also when the Erie Railroad began replacing its 4-4-0s in freight service with 2-8-0s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The railroads had found that the 2-8-0 could move trains twice as heavy at half the cost of its predecessors.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] From a financial standpoint at the time, the choice of the 2-8-0 as new freight locomotive was therefore clear.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The S160 Class of the United States Army Transportation Corps was built by American manufacturers and was designed for use in Europe for heavy freight work during the Second World War.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] A total of 2,120 of this class was built and they worked on railroads across the world.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Production of the 2-8-0 type in the United States totalled more than 23,000 locomotives, of which 12,000 were export versions.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Great Northern Railway Consolidation No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 1147 is on display in a park in Wenatchee, Washington.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Maine Central class W 2-8-0 locomotives numbered 501 and 519 were officially property of the European and North American Railway (E&NA) as a condition of the lease of that company by the Maine Central Railroad.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] While all other Maine Central steam locomotives were scrapped when replaced by diesel locomotives, these two survived as a lease obligation until Maine Central purchased E&NA in 1955.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The advantages of preservation were recognized by that date, so No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 501 is awaiting restoration to operating condition at the Conway Scenic Railroad in Conway, New Hampshire, and No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 519 was on display at the Steamtown National Historic Site in Scranton, Pennsylvania.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 895, a 2-8-0 *Consolidation* locomotive built by ALCO in 1913 is on static display at Roseland Park in Baytown, Texas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 895 was retired after 44 years of service and donated by Southern Pacific Railroad to the Robert E.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Lee High School Key Club, then towed on temporary tracks to its current location at Roseland Park in April, 1957.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Southern Pacific 2579 is on static display under a shed in Klamath Falls, Oregon.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 545 "A.J Cromwell", built in 1888, is preserved at the B&O Railroad Museum in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Southern Pacific Railroad's locomotive No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 2562 was built by the Baldwin Locomotive Works in 1909, serial No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It is on exhibit in the Arizona Railway Museum in Chandler, Arizona.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The locomotive and its tender are listed in the National Register of Historic Places, reference No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Atchison, Topeka, and Santa Fe Railroad's class 759 locomotive No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] When active, it was used on the railroad's mainline between Chicago and the west.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 761 is plinthed next to the historic Wickenburg, Arizona, train depot that is now the town's visitor center.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 769 is currently on static display in Madrid, New Mexico, but is awaiting a future restoration to run on the Santa Fe Southern Railway.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 346 is operational at the Colorado Railroad Museum.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 318 is also on static display at the same museum, along with Denver, Leadville and Gunnison 191.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 315 is operational and owned by the Durango Historical Society.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Colorado & Southern (C&S) narrow-gauge No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 60 is on display in Idaho Springs, Colorado, while C&S No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 630, is run and maintained in Chattanooga, Tennessee, by the Tennessee Valley Railroad Museum.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 2014, this locomotive participated in the Norfolk Southern 21st Century Steam program.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1962, the Arcade and Attica Railroad purchased an ALCO-build locomotive from the Boyne City Railroad in Michigan.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The locomotive, now numbered 18, is billed as the last operating steam excursion in New York State.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Three out of the four SC-1 hogs from the Lake Superior and Ishpeming survived being scrapped.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 33 has been restored by the Hocking Valley Scenic Railway, before being purchased by the Age of Steam Roundhouse in Sugarcreek, Ohio, where it operates today.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 35 has been on static display at the Illinois Railway Museum in Union, Illinois since 1985.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 1991, the Western Maryland Scenic Railroad, based in Cumberland, Maryland, acquired SC-1 class No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The locomotive was restored to operating condition and cosmetically changed to look like an original Western Maryland 2-8-0.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The locomotive was renumbered 734 in honor, so to speak, of the H-7 (Nos.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 701-764) class of 2-8-0 that the Western Maryland harbored and of which none was preserved, although it has an overall appearance of an H-8.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Over the years it was overworked and according to the WMSR 734 is in very poor mechanical condition.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It was pulled from service officially in 2016.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 734 is nicknamed, is undergoing restoration to operating condition.
