[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 19 is on static display in Frisco, Texas, and No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 20 is on static display in Allan, Texas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Other preserved Ex-LS&I 2-8-0s include No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 21, which is being rebuilt in Wisconsin, No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 22, which is on static display at the Mid-Continent Railway Museum in North Freedom, Wisconsin, No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 23, which is stored at the Empire State Railway Museum in Phoenicia, New York, and No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 24, which is on static display at the National Railroad Museum in Green Bay, Wisconsin.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 561 is on static display along US Highway 81 in Columbus, Nebraska.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 423 is on static display on 10th street in Gering, Nebraska.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 6072 is on static display at Wyman park in Fort Riley, Kansas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 40, built in December 1925 for the Lancaster and Chester Railroad in South Carolina, and later purchased by the Cliffside Railroad in North Carolina, now pulls scenic excursion trains at the New Hope and Ivyland Railroad in New Hope, Pennsylvania, which opened in August, 1966.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 60, built in August 1937 by the American Locomotive Company in Schenectady, New York, is currently operated on the Black River and Western Railroad in Ringoes, New Jersey.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 60 originally operated on the Great Western Railway of Colorado.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 1702, built in 1942 for the United States Army, was purchased by the Great Smoky Mountains Railroad (GSMR) of Bryson City, North Carolina, in the mid-1990s for use on its scenic railway excursions.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In October 2012, a partnership formed between GSMR and Swain County to provide funding to restore the locomotive.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] In 2013, a complete restoration was launched and the locomotive returned to service during summer 2016.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 1187, of the class R, later H3, is on display at the Railroad Museum of Pennsylvania in Strasburg, Lancaster County, Pennsylvania.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] This class is described in detail in the book *Set Up Running: The Life of a Pennsylvania Railroad Engineman 1904-1949*.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] The Valley Railroad, operating in Connecticut as the Essex Steam Train and Riverboat, has one 2-8-0, No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 97 built in 1923 by the American Locomotive Company’s Cooke Machine Works in Paterson, New Jersey for use in Cuba.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It stayed at Cooke until the Works’ closure in 1926 and started service on the Birmingham and Southeastern Railroad in Alabama as No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] It ran various excursions on the Vermont Railway and New Haven Railroad in the late 1960s under a private owner.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 97 arrived in Essex in 1970 initially operating between 1973 and 2010.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 29 is currently operational on the Virginia and Truckee Railroad headquartered in Virginia City, Nevada.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] Two USATC *General Pershing* locomotives survive in the United States.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 28 is currently undergoing repair to run again at the Texas State Railroad in Palestine, Texas, and No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/2-8-0] 101 is on static display at the National Railroad Museum in Green Bay, Wisconsin.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] The **AAR wheel arrangement** system is a method of classifying locomotive (or unit) wheel arrangements that was developed by the Association of American Railroads.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Essentially a simplification of the European UIC classification, it is widely used in North America to describe diesel and electric locomotives (including third-rail electric locomotives).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] It is not used for steam locomotives anywhere, which use the Whyte notation instead, except geared steam locomotives, which are instead classified by their model and their number of trucks (bogies in Commonwealth English).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] The AAR system (like UIC) counts axles, unlike Whyte notation, which counts wheels.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Letters refer to powered axles, with 'A' representing one powered axle, 'B' two consecutive powered axles on the same truck (bogie), 'C' three consecutive powered axles on the same truck, and so on.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] Numbers are used to show unpowered (idler) axles.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] "1" refers to one idler axle, and "2" to two idler axles in a row on the one truck (bogie), and so on.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] A dash ("–") separates trucks (bogies) or wheel assemblies.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/aar-wheel-arrangement] A plus sign ("+") refers to articulation, either by connecting bogies with span bolsters or by connecting individual locomotives via solid drawbars instead of couplers, or in multiple units, where each unit is permanently coupled to the other.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] The **Adams axle** is a form of radial axle for rail locomotives that enable them to negotiate curves more easily.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] It was invented by William Bridges Adams and patented in 1865.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] The invention uses axle boxes that slide on an arc in shaped horn blocks, so allowing the axle to slide out to either side.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] This is similar to the movement of a Bissell truck, but with the notional centre point of the curve being where the pivot of the truck would be.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] This design, using slide bearings, is more expensive than one employing a shaft, but takes up less space.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] Notwithstanding the 1865 comparative trials of the two inventors' products, there is some confusion over the inventor of the axle.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/adams-axle] *Lexicon der Eisenbahn* cites William Adams (1823-1904) as the inventor.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The **Arnoux system** is a train articulation system, for turning on railroad tracks, invented by Jean-Claude-Républicain Arnoux and patented in France in 1838.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux was the chief engineer of the Ligne de Sceaux, which was originally built with very tight radii in the area around Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] With the support of the French Academy of Sciences, Arnoux devised a new articulation system that allowed train wheels to turn, the *système ferroviaire dit Arnoux* ("Arnoux rail system"), and the Ligne de Sceaux was built to test his prototypes.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The line started commercial use in 1846, but the operating cost and the use of a broad gauge of 1,750 mm (5 ft 8+7⁄8 in) meant that it was not taken up more widely.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The invention of the bogie made it redundant.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] When railways were in their infancy, trains comprised a steam locomotive and one or more railway carriages with two fixed axles.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] As speeds increased, this design caused significant wear to the track and instability in the track ballast.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] To resolve these faults, Arnoux proposed a system of *essieux articulés* ("Articulated axles") where the yaw angle of the wheels was reduced to basically zero.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux adapted the system used on horse-carts, which pivoted each axle at its centre, to be applied equally over the two axles together.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux devised a system of chains and pulleys so that each of the wheels' correctly adjusted in yaw through the curve: as soon as the leading axle started to turn, all other axles would also turn by the same amount.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] However, this was flawed since not all carriages in a long train are on the same part of the curve.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] A compromise was to use pulleys of different diameters, with guide wheels on the locomotive to control their motion.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Also, using a broad gauge of 1,750 mm (5 ft 8+7⁄8 in) was expected to give greater stability.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] This system was not suitable for steam locomotives, so Arnoux invented a separate system for them.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The locomotives had a 2-4-2 wheel arrangement and the driving wheels were flangeless.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The carrying wheels were arranged to pivot and were controlled by near-horizontal guide wheels.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Arnoux applied for his patent, number 8342, on 28 March 1838.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Trials took place at Saint-Mandé between 1839 and 1840 in a 1 km (0.62 mi) circuit constructed by Alexis Dulong.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] These trials successfully demonstrated the stability and safety of the system.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Public bodies, the Duke of Aumale and numerous members of the French Academy of Sciences, including François Arago.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] After this experience, Arnoux was awarded the *Grand Prix de Mécanique* ("Grand Prize for Mechanical Engineering") by the Institute.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] At the suggestion of François Arago, the Arnoux system was implemented on the Ligne de Sceaux from Paris to Sceaux, Hauts-de-Seine.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] On 5 September 1844, Arnoux and the Minister of Public Works signed a contract to build and operate the line.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The line began service in 1846, starting from the *Barrière d'enfer* ("Hell's Gate") (see Denfert-Rochereau station) with a curved passenger building of 25-metre (82 ft) radius on a balloon loop to allow trains to reverse direction.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The route then had its first stop at Arcueil, then Bourg-la-Reine on a 30-metre (98 ft) radius curve.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The incline towards Sceaux was straight until the station at Fontenay-aux-Roses, then had a succession of curves at 63,-70-and-50-metre radii (207, 230 and 164 ft); the gradient was up to 11 mm/m (1.1%, 1:91), which was significant.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] All together the line was 10.5 km (6.5 mi) long.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The problem of curves was solved using bogies, which were invented in the United States shortly after adopting rail transport, but this was unknown in Europe at the time.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The Arnoux system bears some similarity to Cleminson's patent system, as both are designed to keep the axles radial to the curvature of the track.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Talgo utilises independent wheels mounted in a "rodal" between cars.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Linkage rods keep the "rodal" aligned tangentially with the track.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Like Arnoux, this system originally utilised (Iberian) broad gauge tracks, but recent versions are used on standard gauge or utilise variable gauge.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Current research may rework the Arnoux system by replacing its mechanical steering linkages with modern electronic systems.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The most promising approach places independent traction motors in each wheel which not only propel the vehicle but also steer the individual wheelset by means of torque vectoring.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] This gives reduced weight and complexity over current bogies whilst also reducing wear on both the train and track.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] Examples include Actiwheel and their proposed running gear for the Next Generation Train.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arnoux-system] The track was replaced overnight with standard gauge in May 1891.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] The **Caprotti valve gear** is a type of steam engine valve gear invented in the early 1920s by Italian architect and engineer Arturo Caprotti.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] It uses camshafts and poppet valves rather than the piston valves used in other valve gear.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] While basing his design on automotive valves, Caprotti made several significant departures from this design to adapt the valves for steam.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] Having agreed a joint-venture with Worcester-based engineering company Heenan & Froude from 1938, Heenan & Froude fully acquired Caprotti post-World War II in 1947.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] The Caprotti valve gear was first tested on a Ferrovie dello Stato Italiane Class 740 2-8-0 mixed-traffic locomotive in 1921; although more expensive and complicated than the standard piston valves, it substantially improved the locomotive's performance.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] Until the 1930s it was fitted on some 334 FS locomotives and on 77 narrow-gauge locomotives of other companies; of the former, some were new-builds, the others were rebuilds of non-superheated compound locomotives.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] Given their need for more complex and expensive maintenance, most of these locomotives were generally withdrawn from service before those with Walschaerts valve gear, in the 1960s.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] In August 1926, the London, Midland and Scottish Railway equipped four-cylinder 4-6-0 locomotive no.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] 5908 of the *Claughton* Class with Caprotti valve gear and poppet valves.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] It was found that the Caprotti-fitted locomotives were more economical on coal and water than those with Walschaerts valve gear, but it was later found that some of the losses of the Walschaerts locomotives was due to leakage of steam past the valve heads, where a single wide ring was used.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] New piston valves having several narrow rings were fitted to one locomotive, and it was then found that the Walschaerts valve gear could be just as economical as the Caprotti, but with considerably less cost of fitment.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] No more *Claughtons* were fitted with Caprotti valve gear, and the ten locomotives were withdrawn in 1935–36.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] On the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER), two 4-6-0 locomotives of LNER Class B3 were rebuilt with Caprotti valve gear in 1929, followed by a further two in 1938–39.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] These locomotives also had four cylinders, and the poppet valves were mounted vertically, two at each end of each cylinder.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] One of the first pair of locomotives was rebuilt with Walschaerts valve gear in 1943, but the other three ran with Caprotti valve gear until withdrawal in 1946–47.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] In the 1950s, Caprotti valve gear was improved and this **British Caprotti valve gear** was fitted to the last two British Railways-built 'Black Fives' 44686/7, the last 30 BR Standard Class 5s, numbers 73125-54, and the unique BR Standard Class 8 71000 *Duke of Gloucester*.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] Results were mixed, with the performance of the *Duke of Gloucester* being particularly disappointing.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] That was later found to be due to errors elsewhere in the design and construction of the locomotive.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] Although more expensive to manufacture than its rivals, the improved Caprotti valve gear is considerably more efficient than any other.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] A major improvement is that much of the mechanism is enclosed, leading to reduced wear and tear from the harsh steam locomotive environment, and completely independent control of admission and exhaust.
[src:caprotti-valve-gear/caprotti-valve-gear] The restored *Duke of Gloucester*, with its flaws eliminated, has proved the concept.
